Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Case called at 3:49 p.m. 
Court addresses Paige that she was previously ordered to pay court costs relative to this action.  Outstanding balance of $323 owed; review date was on March 6, 2017, Paige left before case was called.  Paige indicates no money with her, no job.  Court addresses Paige to "get act together."  Court quashes warrant and will give additional time to pay, would have been easy to have her locked up until she paid.  Court tells her she must do something to have an active role to get this taken care of.  Don't mind giving benefit of doubt, but "don't prove me wrong."  
Court sets for review - Monday, June 26, 2017 at 3:00 p.m.  If the balance is paid, Paige does not have to appear.  If not paid, appearance is mandatory with a detailed, compelling explanation of what her plan is.
